1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:22,700
 All right, shall we talk some Deleuze?

2
00:00:23,800 --> 00:00:24,280
 Sure.

3
00:00:24,420 --> 00:00:24,660
 Sure.

4
00:00:26,760 --> 00:00:27,560
 A little Deleuze.

5
00:00:27,560 --> 00:00:37,140
 This is good because I really want your guys' help on these things because – so the time thing is always hard for me.

6
00:00:37,300 --> 00:00:38,720
 I mean I just have a hard time.

7
00:00:38,780 --> 00:00:39,920
 I don't know why it is.

8
00:00:40,000 --> 00:00:46,280
 Like there's no other major conceptual thing that I have a harder time with than thinking about time.

9
00:00:47,240 --> 00:00:49,820
 That's the name of this episode then, hard times with time.

10
00:00:52,040 --> 00:00:52,900
 The time thing.

11
00:00:52,900 --> 00:01:06,240
 I mean that's – I'm just interested in – I'm really interested in us just talking through it because I don't really – I don't have a good – I feel like when I understand some of these series, I kind of have like a – I don't know.

12
00:01:06,300 --> 00:01:13,820
 At least some sort of mental picture, a mental model of the conceptual dynamics and for whatever reason – and it's not just Deleuze.

13
00:01:13,940 --> 00:01:15,320
 It's anything that I read on time.

14
00:01:15,360 --> 00:01:21,060
 I just have a very hard – it's very difficult for me to conceptualize time.

15
00:01:21,260 --> 00:01:22,140
 It's a country song.

16
00:01:22,300 --> 00:01:23,900
 Hard time with time.

17
00:01:25,260 --> 00:01:25,660
 Yeah.

18
00:01:26,080 --> 00:01:30,140
 No, I had a lot more trouble with that second series than with the alcohol one.

19
00:01:30,260 --> 00:01:47,800
 I felt like the first one for today was not straightforward but it was kind of more impressionistic or poetic and you could – I found myself latching on to a few of the key little arguments or like the imagery of that first series for today.

20
00:01:47,800 --> 00:01:58,360
 And then the second one was pretty highly technical and was going through all the dynamics of Kronos and then Aeon and I didn't feel – it wasn't like I wasn't understanding it.

21
00:01:58,460 --> 00:02:08,160
 It's just that – I mean like you're saying, I think the most interesting thing I – personally I can say about time is that I don't really have anything interesting to say about it.

22
00:02:08,380 --> 00:02:14,300
 It's just like I don't really know what to do with some of that conceptual material.

23
00:02:14,760 --> 00:02:16,540
 But maybe Nathaniel has the answers.

24
00:02:16,700 --> 00:02:17,840
 I don't have the answers.

25
00:02:17,920 --> 00:02:30,660
 I like thinking through time just because it's – when I can see it, it feels great and then when I can't, I feel totally disoriented and I can't even utter a single sentence about it.

26
00:02:31,040 --> 00:02:43,240
 But reading something like this is – it gets me in those – it allows me to position myself where I can get those little glimpses of what's going on and I love that.

27
00:02:43,920 --> 00:02:45,140
 I get the glimpses.

28
00:02:45,140 --> 00:02:46,560
 I mean I get the glimpses too.

29
00:02:48,260 --> 00:02:57,740
 I mean for example, and I – at least for me, the thing that is most helpful for thinking about time is usually Derrida.

30
00:02:59,020 --> 00:03:15,280
 And so in terms of like the Kronos thing, I think of it in terms of Derrida where Derrida has this line in something where he says, you know, every thinking about the future is always of a future present, which is it conceptualizes the future as another moment that's – that it's just not here yet.

31
00:03:15,660 --> 00:03:19,180
 Or the past as something that is – it's a present.

32
00:03:19,340 --> 00:03:23,760
 It's just not – it's already, you know, behind us or something like that.

33
00:03:23,820 --> 00:03:25,600
 So it's all conceptualized in terms of present.

34
00:03:26,000 --> 00:03:27,920
 So that to me made sense, right?

35
00:03:28,000 --> 00:03:32,580
 Like it's, you know, that Kronos image of it's just a series of presents.

36
00:03:32,720 --> 00:03:41,400
 And then, you know, he talks about the Zeus view, the sort of God's eye view where all of that would count as present.

37
00:03:42,040 --> 00:03:46,560
 And so that's the sort of – the unity of, you know, the universal unity.

38
00:03:46,580 --> 00:03:47,500
 The eternal present.

39
00:03:47,860 --> 00:03:48,000
 Yeah.

40
00:03:48,120 --> 00:03:48,440
 Right.

41
00:03:48,560 --> 00:03:50,660
 Like – and so I feel like I get that part.

42
00:03:50,740 --> 00:03:53,260
 I mean I get that component of Kronos.

43
00:03:53,740 --> 00:03:59,240
 And then I also get the sort of critique dimension of the eon, which is that there's no presence.

44
00:03:59,680 --> 00:04:02,760
 There's no present in the eon version.

45
00:04:04,040 --> 00:04:04,400
 Right, right.

46
00:04:04,400 --> 00:04:16,700
 And that to me is – it just – the way I understand it is it's just kind of a deconstruction of the notion of presence, like fairly simply, you know, which is that even that present moment is always split.

47
00:04:17,940 --> 00:04:22,060
 And it's sort of coming to be passing away in Heidegger's terminology.

48
00:04:22,880 --> 00:04:24,040
 So I get that.

49
00:04:24,100 --> 00:04:31,460
 I get that sense of like on the one hand, there are these presents, some of which we call the past, some of which we call the future, some of which we call the present.

50
00:04:31,880 --> 00:04:35,120
 On the other hand, there is this sense of which there's no presence ever.

51
00:04:35,720 --> 00:04:40,840
 There is only the dehescences, like the term that Derrida uses at the heart of it.

52
00:04:41,140 --> 00:04:46,480
 So I get – and I took that to be like the basic kind of architecture of the two.

53
00:04:46,760 --> 00:04:54,300
 But there is a lot more going on there that I feel like I'm just – other than – you know, I get those – the basic points.

54
00:04:55,320 --> 00:05:02,080
 But I feel like I don't really know what else to say about time other than kind of deconstructing presence.

55
00:05:02,220 --> 00:05:04,340
 I mean that's the Derridian in me.

56
00:05:04,420 --> 00:05:06,260
 It's like, hey, the presence is never simply present.

57
00:05:06,700 --> 00:05:13,520
 And, you know, I mean there's a way in which that's a kind of like 16-year-old stoner point, right?

58
00:05:13,740 --> 00:05:19,280
 Like – so like the minute you say now, it's already – you know, like all of that kind of thinking.

59
00:05:19,520 --> 00:05:30,000
 So – and that's about as far as I go conceptually in terms of – even in this chapter, I realize – I get the sense that there's a lot more to their interplay and dynamics.

60
00:05:30,140 --> 00:05:32,040
 But I don't really have a sense of what it is.

61
00:05:32,260 --> 00:05:35,160
 So – and I didn't expect either of you guys to have an answer.

62
00:05:35,240 --> 00:05:39,520
 I just figured we'll talk through the shit and through some of the examples and out of that is going to come some stuff.

63
00:05:39,680 --> 00:05:43,580
 So it wasn't like, hey, quick, come up with something, you know.

64
00:05:48,220 --> 00:06:05,180
 One of the things I would really like to think through, you know, the two notions of time and the relationship to each other, not just in and of it for itself, but also the version of Kronos that we get here is so different than the version of Kronos that typically traffics.

65
00:06:05,280 --> 00:06:10,920
 And I think we talked about this in a few episodes ago, but I don't want to just say there are two different versions of Kronos.

66
00:06:10,980 --> 00:06:13,820
 I kind of want to figure out the hinge that that links the two.

67
00:06:14,040 --> 00:06:14,760
 Well, let's do it.

68
00:06:14,860 --> 00:06:15,060
 Right.

69
00:06:15,700 --> 00:06:16,000
 Cool.

70
00:06:16,440 --> 00:06:24,320
 Well, first of all, I mean this is a much more complex Kronos, right, than the one that I'm familiar with, right?

71
00:06:24,380 --> 00:06:29,900
 I mean how would we define Kronos in its most vulgar form, you know?

72
00:06:29,900 --> 00:06:38,440
 I would say to vulgarize it, you would say, you know, time is some natural thing that is constantly unfolding.

73
00:06:38,880 --> 00:06:46,100
 And then Kronos is the scientific measurement of the unfolding of one of the two major dimensions of reality.

74
00:06:46,480 --> 00:06:54,160
 And it's just sort of the regular realization, the sequencing of that, of what is otherwise an undifferentiated movement.

75
00:06:54,160 --> 00:07:00,420
 And you're adding a sort of a system to differentiate it, you know, in terms of seconds, minutes, hours, years, whatever.

76
00:07:01,900 --> 00:07:02,320
 Right, right.

77
00:07:02,360 --> 00:07:07,440
 And then there would be an absolute separability between those moments, right?

78
00:07:07,800 --> 00:07:13,580
 So chronologically, from past to present to future, each moment is separate and separable.

79
00:07:14,020 --> 00:07:15,000
 Absolutely, right?

80
00:07:15,080 --> 00:07:19,580
 There's no folding in that kind of vulgar notion of Kronos.

81
00:07:19,580 --> 00:07:21,140
 Well, I mean, it depends on how you look at it.

82
00:07:21,220 --> 00:07:27,360
 Like if you look at it sort of as – so take any unit of time, right, which would have to have a duration.

83
00:07:27,360 --> 00:07:28,760
 So it could not be the aeon.

84
00:07:28,880 --> 00:07:34,720
 It could not be, you know, the pure line without thickness.

85
00:07:35,000 --> 00:07:42,960
 Like any unit of time in the vulgar – in the scientific notion of chronology would have to have a duration, right?

86
00:07:43,000 --> 00:07:43,900
 It has a thickness to it.

87
00:07:44,420 --> 00:07:47,280
 And then that thickness would have to encapsulate everything in there.

88
00:07:47,340 --> 00:07:49,880
 And this is obviously sort of like introducing those paradox in there.

89
00:07:49,880 --> 00:07:57,240
 It's like, all right, how do you – how are you going to singularize, you know, it's always infinitely more dividable, right?

90
00:07:57,360 --> 00:08:02,720
 And you're not going to ever be able to get to sort of like the absolute, you know, atomic unit of time.

91
00:08:03,240 --> 00:08:17,300
 But I do think that with it – I think that that apparatus invites its own complication in that – like take a scientifically deterministic paradigm.

92
00:08:17,300 --> 00:08:28,360
 That would say – take any snapshot and you would say that it contains every cause that led to this moment.

93
00:08:29,680 --> 00:08:35,040
 I mean – or it is the expression of every – the sum total of every cause in the universe that led to this moment.

94
00:08:35,040 --> 00:08:44,080
 And it contains in it the causality that will lead to every effect, you know, in the future.

95
00:08:44,360 --> 00:08:54,580
 So in a way, even that sort of vulgar sense of chronology sort of collapses all futures and pasts into itself.

96
00:08:55,580 --> 00:09:04,040
 Yeah, well, it certainly invites its own critique at least, which kind of feeds into the version of Aeon that's elucidated here.

97
00:09:04,120 --> 00:09:05,920
 But yeah, I think you're right.

98
00:09:06,280 --> 00:09:17,660
 The really vulgar version of Kronos for me almost like just leaves out any notion of futurity or at least if it's – if the future – the future because of that notion of causality, right?

99
00:09:17,660 --> 00:09:27,440
 Like the future is either totally determined by the – you know, by a certain whatever version of causality or it's completely unknown, right?

100
00:09:27,500 --> 00:09:29,040
 It's totally unpredictable.

101
00:09:29,240 --> 00:09:37,260
 That seems to be the two – so it's like you only get past and present in that – the kind of standard version of Kronos, linear.

102
00:09:37,800 --> 00:09:38,200
 So –

103
00:09:38,200 --> 00:09:38,880
 Yeah, yeah.

104
00:09:38,940 --> 00:09:46,480
 I mean my version of the vulgar I think is a little bit different and maybe this is where – this is my starting point maybe is just one of confusion.

105
00:09:46,480 --> 00:09:57,480
 Because I sort of think of a conventional understanding of time as being – time is just this thing sort of removed from life.

106
00:09:58,420 --> 00:10:04,120
 Like life happens and time becomes this way of measuring it, right?

107
00:10:04,180 --> 00:10:16,460
 Time is this sort of transcendent abstract series of divisions of whatever size that becomes just sort of ways of measuring – in other words, time is not embedded in bodies.

108
00:10:16,480 --> 00:10:35,080
 Time is just the sort of way that we attempt – so for instance, when you said the two major forces, you know, space and time, I always feel like I understand that for space but I don't really understand that for time because I – my sort of intuition – and by the way, I think this is wrong, this intuition.

109
00:10:35,240 --> 00:10:35,680
 I mean let me be clear.

110
00:10:35,680 --> 00:10:35,780
 I mean let me be clear.

111
00:10:35,780 --> 00:10:41,500
 But like is that time is not part of the interaction of bodies.

112
00:10:41,500 --> 00:10:45,720
 It is just a term for describing the fact that things move, right?

113
00:10:45,720 --> 00:10:52,660
 Like it's kind of like a transcendent category of – again, you can have seconds, hours, years, you know, you can have whatever.

114
00:10:53,160 --> 00:11:00,260
 But it's like a line that exists above the world that moves, you know, with an arrow in one direction, right?

115
00:11:00,300 --> 00:11:05,240
 Like that it can be divided however it wants to be divided, that it's not time.

116
00:11:05,240 --> 00:11:13,720
 So I remember for me it was really kind of transformative when – and this is probably 20 years ago and I can't remember.

117
00:11:13,840 --> 00:11:20,320
 It might have been Bergson where I started to think of time as being a component of bodies' interactions.

118
00:11:20,680 --> 00:11:23,680
 Like that's what it means for relations.

119
00:11:24,160 --> 00:11:26,720
 Relations mean time, right?

120
00:11:26,720 --> 00:11:43,100
 Like that's where time is in fact located at that kind of notion of primordial relationality because otherwise to me, like I said, time just seems like it's extracted and removed and it just is a sort of measuring operation for like, yeah, life goes on as it goes on.

121
00:11:43,380 --> 00:11:46,840
 But time is this sort of the thing – a thing hanging above them.

122
00:11:50,680 --> 00:12:01,840
 So you couldn't say that time goes on or happens or any other verb without a sense of time being embedded into it, right?

123
00:12:01,900 --> 00:12:20,660
 So, I mean, I think you would have to look at Kant as the kind of pivotal figure and say sort of like pre-Kant, you would – or at least, you know, this is the sort of story that Kant would tell is that pre-Kant, you know, we just think of time and space as the two natural dimensions of reality.

124
00:12:21,680 --> 00:12:30,080
 And then, you know, we then have extra language that then represents those realities and measures them.

125
00:12:30,620 --> 00:12:33,760
 And, you know, you can – I can measure meters and I can measure seconds.

126
00:12:34,020 --> 00:12:37,920
 But that's just measuring something that already exists out there in the world.

127
00:12:37,980 --> 00:12:44,480
 And frankly, this is, you know, for sort of everything under the paradigm of Newtonian physics.

128
00:12:44,680 --> 00:12:49,660
 You would say that's just – that's just what time – like time and space are just those things, right?

129
00:12:49,660 --> 00:13:14,740
 Now, obviously, they become much more complicated with Einstein and relativity and – but, you know, Kant, you know, does the Copernican flip and be like, you know, time and space are dimensions or sort of like dividing mechanisms of the human mind that, you know, that sort of vend order or lend an organizing logic to, you know, the numeral realm, right?

130
00:13:15,180 --> 00:13:15,440
 Yeah.

131
00:13:16,100 --> 00:13:25,280
 But then, you know, sort of like when you were talking about the abstracted, you know, arrow, you know, that's – you know, the pre-Kantian discourse, you would say that's not time.

132
00:13:25,840 --> 00:13:29,020
 That's language about time, right?

133
00:13:29,740 --> 00:13:33,360
 And then you would say that, no, time is real.

134
00:13:33,600 --> 00:13:36,500
 It is just – but time equals movement.

135
00:13:36,660 --> 00:13:38,580
 Time equals change.

136
00:13:39,640 --> 00:13:40,040
 Right.

137
00:13:40,240 --> 00:13:42,360
 Isn't that – so I associate that with Heidegger.

138
00:13:42,900 --> 00:13:53,580
 Like to me – and I could be wrong, but, you know, the whole point of, to me, you know, being in time is that being is thrown, right?

139
00:13:53,660 --> 00:13:59,020
 Like being is projected, you know, into an alterity and we can get to the details.

140
00:13:59,160 --> 00:14:06,800
 But I always thought that's the thing – I mean, I got it in Bergson, but Bergson got it from Heidegger, you know, I presume.

141
00:14:08,320 --> 00:14:23,500
 And that that was the transformative moment was that time is installed as a constitutive element, in his case, not just of Dazan, but of presence itself, you know, like that time is a component.

142
00:14:23,680 --> 00:14:27,340
 It is not a transcendent operation that simply describes.

143
00:14:27,760 --> 00:14:31,460
 Interestingly enough, because I don't have that problem with the concept of space.

144
00:14:31,720 --> 00:14:35,840
 Space to me seems obviously like part of body's interactions.

145
00:14:36,700 --> 00:14:44,360
 Time just seems like a secondary element of that spatialization that – because they – these things move, right?

146
00:14:44,440 --> 00:14:51,580
 Like they do things that, you know – so I – and this might be a totally personal idiosyncrasy.

147
00:14:51,640 --> 00:14:52,040
 I don't know.

148
00:14:52,340 --> 00:14:57,220
 But space seems obvious to me why it's a fundamental quality of things.

149
00:14:57,580 --> 00:15:00,200
 Time seems like it has to be added in some way.

150
00:15:00,260 --> 00:15:03,400
 Like it doesn't seem as fundamental to me as space does.

151
00:15:04,020 --> 00:15:29,460
 I see Heidegger and Kant's contributions as being quite different in that, you know, that one of – OK, so Zeno's paradox and the problem of change, you know, introduces a pretty – or sort of like recognizes a pretty major problem with the notion of time, which is, you know, if things are, right?

152
00:15:29,460 --> 00:15:37,800
 In other words, if there are atomistic individual things out there and if things change, how the fuck do these two things happen together, right?

153
00:15:37,800 --> 00:15:41,820
 How does anything ever undergo the process of change?

154
00:15:42,500 --> 00:15:47,580
 And, you know, that the notion of time is the measurement of those changes.

155
00:15:47,860 --> 00:15:53,280
 But the problem with it is that if you ever snapshot any duration of time –

156
00:15:53,280 --> 00:15:53,300
 Right.

157
00:15:53,380 --> 00:15:53,860
 That's right.

158
00:15:54,300 --> 00:15:58,120
 Then, you know, it doesn't look like anything is changing.

159
00:15:58,560 --> 00:15:59,320
 No, it's present.

160
00:15:59,540 --> 00:16:00,040
 Everything is stabilized.

161
00:16:00,640 --> 00:16:02,840
 So that's to me – that's the image.

162
00:16:03,020 --> 00:16:05,740
 Let's call it the cinematic image, right?

163
00:16:05,740 --> 00:16:12,440
 Like, I mean, that to me has always been the image of change, which is presence, presence, presence, presence, presence.

164
00:16:12,860 --> 00:16:14,020
 And it's in the interstices.

165
00:16:14,200 --> 00:16:22,060
 I mean, when you think, like, Deleuze is moving in, it's in the interstices between the frames that you attribute the causal agent of change.

166
00:16:22,520 --> 00:16:25,100
 You just literally never see time.

167
00:16:25,340 --> 00:16:25,760
 The change, yeah.

168
00:16:25,820 --> 00:16:30,300
 Like, you know, because, you know, you see space, right?

169
00:16:30,340 --> 00:16:31,720
 Like, you see it.

170
00:16:31,780 --> 00:16:31,940
 Yeah.

171
00:16:31,940 --> 00:16:34,220
 You don't ever see time.

172
00:16:34,320 --> 00:16:38,340
 Time is just the concatenation of a series of still images.

173
00:16:38,680 --> 00:16:41,300
 You know, the photograph that makes it into a movie, right?

174
00:16:41,380 --> 00:16:42,480
 The flipping of the photograph.

175
00:16:42,780 --> 00:16:45,140
 It was the action of the flipping, right?

176
00:16:45,300 --> 00:16:45,600
 The flipping.

177
00:16:45,600 --> 00:16:47,440
 Because they're all just stills, right?

178
00:16:47,900 --> 00:16:48,300
 That's right.

179
00:16:48,440 --> 00:16:49,440
 Just stills.

180
00:16:50,100 --> 00:16:56,600
 And then Kant doesn't mess with that, at least not from my understanding of Kant.

181
00:16:56,700 --> 00:16:58,060
 He doesn't mess with that so much.

182
00:16:58,200 --> 00:17:13,160
 He just realizes that, you know, that epistemological function, it's not, you know, the sort of, like, the addition isn't a linguistic thing that we then add to an already, like, an existing property of the world.

183
00:17:13,160 --> 00:17:18,500
 But it is a mental processing, a mental act of organizing or division.

184
00:17:19,420 --> 00:17:31,820
 Like, he doesn't get, he doesn't attend to the motion of being because it's still, like, beings that then move and movement there means, like, displacement, right?

185
00:17:32,100 --> 00:17:35,200
 Like, this holistic object moves from here to there.

186
00:17:35,200 --> 00:17:41,440
 Or, you know, the evolution of an object is, you know, you can only see it in that cinematic version.

187
00:17:41,640 --> 00:17:48,700
 And then the contribution that I see Heidegger adding is, like, being is never equal to itself.

188
00:17:49,400 --> 00:18:04,940
 And, like, this is the major, I mean, I see Heidegger, Deleuze, you know, Brooks on, like, the whole sort of, like, cadre as the ones that their real target is the law of identity, right?

189
00:18:04,980 --> 00:18:09,300
 Not even the law of the excluded middle or the law of non-contradiction.

190
00:18:09,360 --> 00:18:10,480
 Non-contradiction, right.

191
00:18:10,660 --> 00:18:12,040
 But that A doesn't equal A.

192
00:18:12,640 --> 00:18:26,780
 And it's that sort of, like, what Heidegger is doing is saying, like, no, time as change is an integral dimension of being itself, which means that being, like, which is another way of just saying being is becoming.

193
00:18:27,320 --> 00:18:36,600
 Not just, so the distinction there is, for Kant, it's a mental operation that we perform as opposed to an ontological operation for Heidegger.

194
00:18:36,940 --> 00:18:37,220
 Correct.

195
00:18:37,520 --> 00:18:38,320
 Well, yeah.

196
00:18:39,200 --> 00:18:40,620
 Well, I think what.

197
00:18:40,620 --> 00:18:41,380
 Well, ontological in quotation marks.

198
00:18:41,380 --> 00:18:54,660
 But I think that the major difference is that change and movement are still fundamentally matters of displacement.

199
00:18:55,220 --> 00:18:57,200
 A body moves, right?

200
00:18:57,680 --> 00:18:58,040
 Right.

201
00:18:58,240 --> 00:19:00,580
 As opposed to A does not equal A, right?

202
00:19:00,680 --> 00:19:03,040
 Which is to say A body is movement.

203
00:19:03,660 --> 00:19:03,820
 Right.

204
00:19:04,000 --> 00:19:04,980
 A body is movement.

205
00:19:05,220 --> 00:19:06,300
 Which also means –

206
00:19:06,300 --> 00:19:09,760
 Identity is constituted by difference as opposed to identity differs.

207
00:19:10,480 --> 00:19:10,820
 Exactly.

208
00:19:11,220 --> 00:19:27,240
 So that's a really great way of understanding the sort of identity politics, right, like problem and difficulties is that it's always thinking identity in terms of, yes, there are identities and then they go act in the world as opposed to the sort of, you know, philosophy of difference.

209
00:19:27,240 --> 00:19:28,440
 And stuff, which is like, no, no, no.

210
00:19:28,440 --> 00:19:30,020
 There are no identities, right?

211
00:19:30,100 --> 00:19:33,280
 Because identities are always constituted by their own transformation.

212
00:19:33,640 --> 00:19:35,720
 There's no identity that then transforms.

213
00:19:36,300 --> 00:19:40,720
 There is only the self-transformation of a residual identity.

214
00:19:41,300 --> 00:19:43,360
 There's no such thing as a white person.

215
00:19:43,520 --> 00:19:46,120
 There's only the whitening or blacking, right?

216
00:19:46,340 --> 00:19:46,840
 That's right.

217
00:19:47,140 --> 00:19:47,280
 Right.

218
00:19:48,480 --> 00:19:48,800
 Yeah.

219
00:19:49,380 --> 00:20:01,260
 And I think – I mean, another way to describe it, and you guys have basically said this, but like for Heidegger and I think also for Deleuze, time would be internal to being or it would be imminent to being.

220
00:20:01,400 --> 00:20:03,040
 So becoming equals being.

221
00:20:03,040 --> 00:20:05,880
 And for Kant, that wouldn't be the case, right?

222
00:20:05,940 --> 00:20:08,440
 Time is like almost absolutely external.

223
00:20:09,000 --> 00:20:13,360
 It's the noumena that is like the horizon of our thinking.

224
00:20:13,580 --> 00:20:26,460
 And like you said, we can only apply the mental categories, insufficient mental categories to try to grasp what is an inaccessible noumenal dimension of being, right?

225
00:20:26,600 --> 00:20:29,900
 Well, for Kant, importantly, time is not noumenal, right?

226
00:20:30,040 --> 00:20:31,500
 It is mental.

227
00:20:31,740 --> 00:20:43,500
 It is part of the – it is – so all of the faculties of the mind for Kant, judgment, understanding, rationalization, whatever they are, are only possible.

228
00:20:43,800 --> 00:20:44,280
 Imagination.

229
00:20:44,280 --> 00:20:56,680
 Are only possible because of a more fundamental faculty, like a passive faculty that is always spacing and timing, right?

230
00:20:56,680 --> 00:21:01,060
 It's always doing the work of spacing and timing human-lived reality.

231
00:21:01,620 --> 00:21:08,300
 And then it's within that domain that imagination, understanding, reason can then play out, right?

232
00:21:08,300 --> 00:21:13,900
 And it's that shift, I mean, because Kant's the one that says no time is not noumenal.

233
00:21:14,040 --> 00:21:20,000
 Time is not an ontological feature of the noumenal because, I mean, maybe it is, but I fucking don't know.

234
00:21:20,160 --> 00:21:26,860
 But what I can say our experience of time is the activity of the faculties of the mind.

235
00:21:27,280 --> 00:21:36,360
 And again, these faculties are things that we have no conscious control over, unlike the other capacities which we have semi-control over.

236
00:21:36,360 --> 00:21:47,600
 Right, but time would – I mean, so apart from the mental categorizing principles, there would be some function of time in the thing in itself, right?

237
00:21:47,820 --> 00:21:52,700
 I mean, Kant is not a vulgar, like, identitarian sort of thinker, right?

238
00:21:52,740 --> 00:21:56,120
 I mean, the thing in itself has a temporal dimension, I would assume.

239
00:21:56,120 --> 00:21:56,780
 No, no, no, no, no.

240
00:21:57,400 --> 00:22:09,660
 You would have – for him, the ding on zik is unknowable, radically unknowable, which means that our – like, to talk about it temporally would be to already anthropomorphize it.

241
00:22:09,820 --> 00:22:10,820
 Well, that's what I mean, though.

242
00:22:11,020 --> 00:22:18,100
 Like, but it has – I mean, the thing in itself, even if it is temporal, the key part is its inaccessibility, right?

243
00:22:19,040 --> 00:22:24,620
 But you would never be able to say it is temporal or non-temporal, right?

244
00:22:24,800 --> 00:22:34,400
 Like, you – like, the – because any category we have of describing it is already a transformation of the ding on zik, epistemologically.

245
00:22:34,700 --> 00:22:38,900
 Like, in that sense, there would be no such thing as time itself, right?

246
00:22:38,940 --> 00:22:40,980
 There's no time – that doesn't make –

247
00:22:40,980 --> 00:22:43,680
 There's no time itself, there's no space itself, right?

248
00:22:44,280 --> 00:23:08,000
 That's – I mean, that is the major Copernican revolution of Kant is time and space, which up until now, everyone thought were, like, the most fundamental ontological properties of reality itself are actually the most fundamental properties of, yeah, like, faculties of the human mind.

249
00:23:08,000 --> 00:23:11,260
 Of the people, yeah, of human mind, yeah, yeah, yeah.

250
00:23:11,380 --> 00:23:30,060
 I mean, and that's – I feel like at least experientially then we are still in some way in Kant's horizon because what you were talking about earlier, John, about the way that you can kind of easily get a grasp on space, right, because it lends itself to identities, right?

251
00:23:30,060 --> 00:23:38,520
 I mean, space easily allows you to think through identity, whereas time completely unravels any easy notion of identity or a thing.

252
00:23:38,940 --> 00:23:45,280
 So it's like at least day to day, you're kind of living more as Kant than you are as Heidegger or as Deleuze.

253
00:23:45,360 --> 00:23:52,240
 Now, they seem to want to instill that ontological view into our ways of living, right?

254
00:23:52,280 --> 00:23:55,720
 That seems to be part of the ethics of both of their thinking.

255
00:23:56,100 --> 00:24:08,300
 But, I mean, I do think Kant's – you know, even if the categories are strict and by now they seem a little bit outdated, it does seem like we still operate with some of those assumptions.

256
00:24:08,300 --> 00:24:09,600
 I think Kant's are higher rated.

257
00:24:10,660 --> 00:24:11,940
 Oh, yeah, yeah.

258
00:24:12,220 --> 00:24:24,000
 I mean, I think the way I would adjust that a little bit is that they – I think the claim would be that that – Kant's description of those things is a normative one, whether he wants it to be or not.

259
00:24:24,740 --> 00:24:28,080
 And, in fact, it's not that we do experience it that way.

260
00:24:28,160 --> 00:24:32,960
 It's that we have inherited the normative frame for thinking of it that way.

261
00:24:32,960 --> 00:24:37,000
 And so I don't think that Deleuze is offering the sort of more ontological versions.

262
00:24:37,180 --> 00:24:38,380
 Like, there are other versions.

263
00:24:38,540 --> 00:24:46,020
 There are other ways of experiencing that – in fact, I mean, the argument – you know, think of the alcoholism and schizophrenia chapters.

264
00:24:46,120 --> 00:24:48,040
 Like, look, this is how these people lived, right?

265
00:24:48,040 --> 00:24:50,840
 This is Fitzgerald's life is that he's talking about, right?

266
00:24:50,900 --> 00:24:55,080
 This is not – I mean, he uses the novels, but he's talking about Fitzgerald.

267
00:24:56,440 --> 00:25:05,080
 And so this is like these – and that's consistently been the thing for Deleuze is like Matt – you know, Sacher van Massach and Kafka and these figures that are like,

268
00:25:05,560 --> 00:25:07,800
 hey, these people experimented with different ways of living.

269
00:25:08,040 --> 00:25:09,340
 They didn't consciously experiment.

270
00:25:09,420 --> 00:25:12,500
 It wasn't like they said, I will go, you know, try something different.

271
00:25:12,600 --> 00:25:15,860
 It's just they live differently and experience differently.

272
00:25:15,980 --> 00:25:26,320
 And I think that's the thing that interests Deleuze is that there is a philosophy or an ontology implicit in these other ways of living that is different from,

273
00:25:26,480 --> 00:25:29,100
 they say, the normative Kantian mode.

274
00:25:29,260 --> 00:25:34,280
 So that's where I would just say it's not that people don't experience it that way and we really experience it Kantian.

275
00:25:34,400 --> 00:25:38,800
 It's just that there's a bunch of differences, one of which seems to be really normative.

276
00:25:50,000 --> 00:25:52,960
 Deleuze's book on Kant is so good.

277
00:25:53,060 --> 00:25:59,600
 He takes on that normative function within – that sort of like quite fascistic function within Kant that is like,

278
00:25:59,660 --> 00:26:04,620
 all right, you know, I've made the move of saying like these are processes that are sort of like –

279
00:26:04,620 --> 00:26:06,980
 these are mental faculties of the human mind.

280
00:26:07,380 --> 00:26:14,600
 And then he immediately needs to govern them and he wants to create a system because, you know, think about how –

281
00:26:14,600 --> 00:26:21,100
 like in other words, he doesn't sort of appreciate the – like how radical his own claim is.

282
00:26:21,820 --> 00:26:34,820
 And sort of like – or he does and it scares him and he has to sort of domesticate it a little bit by taking the sort of like the unhinged capacity of saying like

283
00:26:34,820 --> 00:26:37,840
 our mental faculties make our experience of the world for us.

284
00:26:37,840 --> 00:26:46,080
 So let's now install reason and understanding as governing these – or like they ought to be governing these things sort of like in the platonic sense.

285
00:26:46,420 --> 00:26:52,000
 But there are sort of the right ways in which these things synthesize with each other and then there are the wrong things.

286
00:26:52,100 --> 00:26:57,820
 We'll call those illusions or errors or whatever else and sort of –

287
00:26:57,820 --> 00:27:10,060
 But he can never quite figure out the way that these syntheses happen and the sort of like – the sort of movement that allows for these faculties to work until he gets to imagination and then third critique.

288
00:27:10,060 --> 00:27:18,460
 And then he has to, again, subjugate imagination under the rule of reason.

289
00:27:19,520 --> 00:27:36,420
 But the brilliant move that Deleuze makes is to show that the very capacity of imagination to make the entire thing work also prevents imagination from simply being subjugated by these other things.

290
00:27:37,060 --> 00:27:51,260
 Actually, the free play of the imagination actually allows for the coordinations, the syntheses that Kant wants as one kind of synthesis among infinite others, right?

291
00:27:52,080 --> 00:28:00,960
 And that's where – I mean, that's why I love that book so much is that it unlocks Kant from Kant.

292
00:28:01,380 --> 00:28:12,860
 One question I have, which is kind of related to what you just said is – so Kant's notion of the unknown, which would be related to the thing in itself, is terrifying.

293
00:28:13,260 --> 00:28:17,080
 The noumena is terrifying, ontologically, it's terrifying, right?

294
00:28:17,100 --> 00:28:19,520
 I mean, that's what drives you to act.

295
00:28:19,900 --> 00:28:23,180
 It's this underbelly of like human existence.

296
00:28:23,580 --> 00:28:25,300
 It's almost existential, not quite.

297
00:28:25,520 --> 00:28:34,500
 But how then do we relate – because there's also an unknown in this first series that we read for today, which – well, I'm not sure.

298
00:28:34,600 --> 00:28:39,360
 I don't know if you would call it an unknown, but there is terror in that first series, right?

299
00:28:39,440 --> 00:28:47,280
 And if it's not attributed to an unknown, it's attributed to that crack in kind of the – in the ontology.

300
00:28:48,100 --> 00:28:58,380
 And I'm just wondering how – because it seems like at a psychoanalytic or experiential level, like I was just saying, that's kind of the reason why I said Kant might still be with us today as well.

301
00:28:58,380 --> 00:29:19,860
 Because it seems like that notion of terror of the unknown, either whether it's due to the ding on Zik or to some – our inability to process temporality, like it feels like we could not just – not collapse Kant and Heidegger, collapse Kant and Balooz.

302
00:29:20,020 --> 00:29:27,340
 I'm just trying to tease out the differences between those – that fear and anxiety and how they operate with both figures.

303
00:29:27,340 --> 00:29:33,860
 That's really helpful because, I mean, Kant doesn't seem particularly invested in fear and anxiety.

304
00:29:33,860 --> 00:29:37,720
 And I think it's because of his commitment to the epistemological nature.

305
00:29:38,200 --> 00:29:51,080
 Like he is totally committed to representation and the ways that – and while he fully commits to the idea that what representation is not is a reproduction of the real,

306
00:29:51,580 --> 00:30:01,920
 he seems quite comfortable with the idea that it's some kind of – representation is a kind of transformation of the real that gives you no access to the real.

307
00:30:02,240 --> 00:30:03,380
 And he's just like – and that's cool.

308
00:30:03,460 --> 00:30:04,760
 We could never know what that is.

309
00:30:05,140 --> 00:30:06,980
 You know, we have – so let's not even try.

310
00:30:07,340 --> 00:30:08,140
 Set it aside.

311
00:30:08,140 --> 00:30:23,780
 And then everything is all about the sort of the well-functioning or the poor functioning of the world that our faculties create in – for us to experience phenomenologically and epistemologically.

312
00:30:23,780 --> 00:30:37,860
 But I think what the existentialist movement and what you're talking about here with the notion of the crack is that this is not some parallel epistemological realm of representations.

313
00:30:38,500 --> 00:30:49,800
 That the activity of representation or translation or reproduction of the real does not create a stark divide, right?

314
00:30:49,900 --> 00:30:57,240
 There are always cracks, unrepresentable cracks, unreproducible cracks that are running through it.

315
00:30:57,740 --> 00:31:01,240
 That – like this is the very possibility of madness.

316
00:31:01,780 --> 00:31:04,600
 Well, I mean, so now we're talking about the sublime, right?

317
00:31:04,640 --> 00:31:13,780
 Like we're talking about – I mean, so to me, part of the question then would be like in Kant, what's the – what's the relation between noumena and the sublime?

318
00:31:13,780 --> 00:31:20,180
 If the sublime is the experience of the limits of representation, right?

319
00:31:20,260 --> 00:31:22,120
 Like God, for example.

320
00:31:22,900 --> 00:31:23,020
 Right.

321
00:31:23,700 --> 00:31:26,240
 Derrida loves that phrase, God, for example.

322
00:31:26,780 --> 00:31:33,160
 But, yeah, I mean, so the experience of the sublime, which is an experience of terror, you know?

323
00:31:33,260 --> 00:31:35,320
 I mean, that's how you describe it.

324
00:31:35,520 --> 00:31:41,740
 It is that sort of the realization of the incapacity of representation to contain.

325
00:31:42,200 --> 00:31:44,280
 It just – you can't image God.

326
00:31:44,460 --> 00:31:46,120
 It's just not possible.

327
00:31:46,600 --> 00:31:50,160
 But the impossibilities are located in very different places.

328
00:31:50,160 --> 00:31:56,360
 It is that God is not the – a crack in that edifice for Kant.

329
00:31:56,880 --> 00:32:04,520
 It is the making infinite of the faculties themselves, right?

330
00:32:04,860 --> 00:32:11,260
 It's sort of like, you know, when the faculties converge in such and such a way to like – to imagine the infinite, right?

331
00:32:11,600 --> 00:32:15,920
 Well, then, you know, that's – the infinity has nothing to do with the Ding on Zik.

332
00:32:16,140 --> 00:32:21,500
 That is itself, right, a concept that is too big.

333
00:32:21,760 --> 00:32:25,300
 The concept of infinity can't be contained by the concept of infinity, right?

334
00:32:25,460 --> 00:32:25,660
 Right.

335
00:32:25,660 --> 00:32:27,260
 It can't be contained by a concept.

336
00:32:27,480 --> 00:32:30,420
 A concept is inadequate to –

337
00:32:30,420 --> 00:32:30,680
 Right?

338
00:32:31,000 --> 00:32:31,680
 I mean, when you get –

339
00:32:31,680 --> 00:32:36,820
 Which is why, like, you know, when you were a kid, at least when I was a kid, I remember I used to try to think infinity.

340
00:32:36,820 --> 00:32:41,800
 And I would always – it would always induce this kind of vertigo of, like, you know –

341
00:32:41,800 --> 00:32:48,040
 That's the sublime, not the sublime of – I mean, I think this is often the way that the sublime is talked about.

342
00:32:48,120 --> 00:32:53,060
 It's sort of like the unrepresentability of the real world, right?

343
00:32:53,380 --> 00:32:57,680
 It is not – my understanding is that is not the Kantian sense of the sublime.

344
00:32:57,680 --> 00:33:10,340
 That when it is, say, induced by something that we might call, like, natural, like, the size of the universe or, you know, like, the Grand Canyon or, like, a hurricane or something like that, that has nothing to do with the noumenal realm.

345
00:33:10,340 --> 00:33:21,980
 That has everything to do with the sort of overwhelmingness of the interplay of, like, sound and color and noise and –

346
00:33:21,980 --> 00:33:22,760
 Scale, size.

347
00:33:22,760 --> 00:33:24,520
 And scale, exactly, right?

348
00:33:24,800 --> 00:33:29,380
 I remember having conversations with you about the vastness of space and the sort of tear that produces –

349
00:33:29,380 --> 00:33:30,700
 Yeah, I fucking hate space.

350
00:33:35,420 --> 00:33:43,400
 Well, that's what I'm saying is that what the sublime does is it points to the limits of representation, not the inability to represent any particular thing.

351
00:33:43,680 --> 00:33:44,280
 Yeah, yes.

352
00:33:44,540 --> 00:33:54,280
 It just says representation itself can't do the – like, there's a point at which, with infinity, with God, with these series of things, like, representation can't do it.

353
00:33:54,380 --> 00:33:56,620
 It just can't operate.

354
00:33:57,040 --> 00:34:07,180
 If you take representation as encapsulation, right, which might make you think – given the fact that these things can't do that, then you might think maybe representation isn't a matter of encapsulation.

355
00:34:07,740 --> 00:34:08,380
 Well, right.

356
00:34:08,500 --> 00:34:10,420
 I mean, that would be – at some point –

357
00:34:10,420 --> 00:34:10,520
 Well, exactly.

358
00:34:10,760 --> 00:34:21,800
 I mean, that to me is – that's like, you know, the 300-year-old – we've had this problem for 300 years, and at some point it's like, well, why don't we start going maybe the purpose of language and thought isn't to represent?

359
00:34:22,460 --> 00:34:33,640
 Like, either that or we're going to do – because to me, that's a lot of what I – I mean, the logic of that is a lot of what I don't like about the sort of – the Zizek types of moves and the Lacanian influence types of moves.

360
00:34:33,960 --> 00:34:46,140
 It's just a perpetual demonstration of the failure to adequately represent, and it's like, well, yeah, either there's a constant process of failure or it's doing something else.

361
00:34:46,400 --> 00:34:48,920
 You know, it's production, you know.

362
00:34:49,120 --> 00:34:49,900
 Right, right.

363
00:34:50,080 --> 00:35:02,500
 Yeah, but I mean for Kant also, like that impasse, so the inability of representations to adequately represent anything, themselves, not even the noumena, that's what actually allows for freedom.

364
00:35:03,060 --> 00:35:07,560
 You know, it's not just like a – it's not just a failure and a paralysis.

365
00:35:07,560 --> 00:35:07,800
 No, that's right.

366
00:35:07,900 --> 00:35:08,660
 No, no, that's right.

367
00:35:08,760 --> 00:35:09,140
 Right, right.

368
00:35:09,140 --> 00:35:09,380
 That's right.

369
00:35:09,480 --> 00:35:27,540
 No, no, so I'm just – I mean, I'm just saying, just to outline this real quick, because one of the weird things about the Ding on Zik is that Kant's formulation basically is that if humans actually had access to the thing in itself, we would become automaton.

370
00:35:28,040 --> 00:35:28,120
 Right.

371
00:35:28,320 --> 00:35:30,320
 So if you actually confront it –

372
00:35:30,320 --> 00:35:30,840
 It's totalization.

373
00:35:31,240 --> 00:35:35,320
 If you can totalize the representation, there's no more work to do.

374
00:35:35,420 --> 00:35:44,100
 It's precisely because of the Zenos – it's precisely because you're like an inch closer and then a half inch closer that you're always getting closer, but you're never going to be there, that there's always somewhere to go.

375
00:35:44,500 --> 00:35:44,780
 Right?

376
00:35:44,900 --> 00:35:48,360
 Like it's what drives – and you're absolutely right.

377
00:35:48,440 --> 00:35:52,320
 Like the notion of lack is an engine for psychoanalysis.

378
00:35:52,320 --> 00:35:56,980
 It's – and it is the lack – the only thing it's ever lacking is totalization, right?

379
00:35:57,060 --> 00:36:00,200
 Like the lack or failure to totalize.

380
00:36:00,840 --> 00:36:05,280
 But again, like the flip side would be maybe it was never even trying to totalize.

381
00:36:05,420 --> 00:36:21,440
 Maybe that's – the game has never been totalization or representation at all, which strikes me as – I mean, that just strikes me as a way more interesting and second line of thinking is what if language was never, ever in the game of representation?

382
00:36:21,440 --> 00:36:24,260
 You know, and instead was in the game of what?

383
00:36:24,400 --> 00:36:28,080
 Making, production, action, whatever, whatever sort of terminology.

384
00:36:28,260 --> 00:36:45,680
 But I take Nate's point to be a little bit different there that – I mean, I don't think that the kind of representation that Kant is after is totalization, totalizing reproduction of the Ding on Zik because, I mean, that's sort of like move one for him.

385
00:36:45,780 --> 00:36:47,420
 No, this is reproduction, right?

386
00:36:47,460 --> 00:36:49,060
 This is transformation.

387
00:36:50,020 --> 00:36:58,920
 And the actual fear there is that if you could have that one-to-one reproduction, then it would be pure determinism.

388
00:36:58,920 --> 00:37:16,720
 And that it is precisely like the mental operation that now creates an entire world out of its perversions, transformations, whatever else of the noumenal realm creates space for movement, creates space for decision freedom.

389
00:37:17,300 --> 00:37:24,060
 And that's what allows for the moral realm to exist at all, that we can make decisions.

390
00:37:25,120 --> 00:37:25,560
 Right.

391
00:37:25,640 --> 00:37:34,660
 But, I mean, that's the failure to totalize representation is the thing that allows for that just a little bit of – a little opening at the end of the circle.

392
00:37:34,780 --> 00:37:36,920
 Like the circle does not close, right?

393
00:37:36,920 --> 00:37:40,920
 If it closed, yeah, you'd have determinism.

394
00:37:41,260 --> 00:37:49,000
 But because it's not closed, there's a perpetual opening, even if it's just a sliver, a perpetual opening that allows for transformation.

395
00:37:49,180 --> 00:37:56,200
 But, again, I mean, to me, that problem gets solved by a conception of multiplicity too, right?

396
00:37:56,300 --> 00:38:06,120
 That you needn't think about like sort of self-contained automaton, totalized automatons bumping into self-contained totalized automatons, right?

397
00:38:06,360 --> 00:38:06,600
 Right.

398
00:38:06,660 --> 00:38:17,820
 Well, all you have is – all you have is the crack or a series or a multiplicity of cracks rather than a – like so he wants to get rid of the circle basically is what Deleuze wants to do, right?

399
00:38:17,860 --> 00:38:23,480
 I mean there's no concept of circularity at least in this previous series, right?

400
00:38:23,500 --> 00:38:29,700
 It's just a line, a series of cracks that enable certain things but there's no telos.

401
00:38:29,700 --> 00:38:34,000
 Right, but think of the difference and that's to me – I mean I – and maybe this is my own weirdness.

402
00:38:34,160 --> 00:38:41,560
 I really don't know but I feel like so much of what people think about in terms of philosophy is given stuff, how do you change it?

403
00:38:41,820 --> 00:38:51,840
 But to me, if you take that other orientation, the question is exactly the opposite which is like given constant transformation, how does shit ever stay the same, right?

404
00:38:51,840 --> 00:38:58,600
 Like how do things cohere enough that we think we're the same people, we think we go back to the same – you know, like so that becomes –

405
00:38:58,600 --> 00:39:05,220
 your problem set becomes completely opposite of the problem set of normal thinking, you know?

406
00:39:05,540 --> 00:39:16,320
 You invert the problematic in a way and I think even just the title of Deleuze's big book, I mean Difference in Repetition, you can see what that does to being in time, right?

407
00:39:16,400 --> 00:39:24,840
 I mean if difference is the ontologically primary principle, then we don't even really – I mean you still have to worry about identity but that's not what you start with.

408
00:39:25,080 --> 00:39:27,800
 No, you start – it's like how do you ever get there?

409
00:39:27,800 --> 00:39:34,420
 How do you ever get to – like how could life desire identity given difference?

410
00:39:35,280 --> 00:39:37,800
 You know, how does it have to coagulate?

411
00:39:37,960 --> 00:39:47,740
 So what are the strata of formations that are necessary in order to produce this thing called consciousness that believes that it's the same as itself, right?

412
00:39:47,740 --> 00:39:54,100
 And so that's a completely opposite problem from – given that consciousness thinks that it is an I.

413
00:39:54,360 --> 00:39:55,220
 So it's exactly the I.

414
00:39:55,300 --> 00:40:07,200
 It's like, you know, given the logic of identity, how do things change versus, you know, how do you ever get to – how do you have to build to the idea of identity?

415
00:40:07,860 --> 00:40:18,640
 You know, so given – and again, I mean to me the hard thing about that is what – change in that second register doesn't mean the same thing as it does in the first, right?

416
00:40:19,060 --> 00:40:22,500
 Change in the first register, and this is usually how we think of it.

417
00:40:22,840 --> 00:40:29,240
 It means an identity that is transformed from point A to point B like the movie clips before.

418
00:40:29,620 --> 00:40:33,680
 But the sense of quote-unquote change in the other one, you don't start with a preexisting identity.

419
00:40:33,680 --> 00:40:37,840
 So it's – and you don't start with even a concept.

420
00:40:38,100 --> 00:40:44,540
 So that's what's hard, I think, is that it is a kind of a-conceptual thinking.

421
00:40:44,720 --> 00:40:44,820
 Yeah.

422
00:40:45,280 --> 00:40:45,720
 You know?

423
00:40:45,920 --> 00:40:46,120
 Yeah.

424
00:40:46,320 --> 00:40:46,480
 Yeah.

425
00:40:46,540 --> 00:40:50,920
 I mean change does not happen to identities for Deleuze at least, right?

426
00:40:51,140 --> 00:40:58,000
 Change would be – change is becoming and that is – I mean it's primordial, I suppose you could say.

427
00:40:58,000 --> 00:41:12,340
 I mean we've kind of covered this at least once, but the challenging thing for me and you can – is like when you think about it at a biological level, like with the notion of autopoiesis or something like that.

428
00:41:12,920 --> 00:41:18,280
 It's like – and this doesn't – it almost feels like the both and move, but it's a little different from that.

429
00:41:19,040 --> 00:41:25,340
 But you kind of have to think the simultaneity, right, of both identity and difference.

430
00:41:25,340 --> 00:41:32,300
 Like because for the possibility of life – and I don't know anything about biology, but you need a cell.

431
00:41:32,480 --> 00:41:41,260
 You need something that's at least provisionally an identity in order for there to be relations between, you know, things.

432
00:41:41,400 --> 00:41:48,960
 But again, like I don't – how you think the priority of that is – I mean it's just confusing, you know, to me at some point.

433
00:41:48,960 --> 00:41:55,620
 I like thinking about that example because, you know, when you say you need a cell, it's the need that you need.

434
00:41:55,700 --> 00:41:58,380
 You need the function of what we call a cell.

435
00:41:58,540 --> 00:42:02,080
 But you would say in the sort of strict sense there are no cells, right?

436
00:42:02,140 --> 00:42:05,240
 There are only the movements and becomings and evolutions.

437
00:42:05,740 --> 00:42:17,320
 But then you need things to sort of intersect or function in such a way as to do the operation that we attribute to this thing called – that we call a cell.

438
00:42:17,400 --> 00:42:20,980
 And that's what I really like about what he's doing with Aeon and Kronos here.

439
00:42:21,060 --> 00:42:30,880
 Just like, you know, it seems to me that what we would call identities are only possible because of events.

440
00:42:31,280 --> 00:42:43,400
 That events are sort of like the logics that rip through or hover over bodies and make, you know, momentary individuating – like that give them sense, right?

441
00:42:43,400 --> 00:42:58,900
 And sense – what is sense other than sort of like a kind of spacing and like introducing this kind of spacing and organizing spacing to things that, you know, just – that doesn't – that actually makes the things of the things.

442
00:42:59,560 --> 00:43:05,320
 Makes the thingness of the things, not the substance of the things but the sort of like the demarcating boundaries of the things.

443
00:43:09,820 --> 00:43:19,700
 I was trying to run through this example in my head when he was talking about the sort of the differences between Kronos and Aeon.

444
00:43:19,980 --> 00:43:29,040
 And I was trying to imagine this in terms of, you know, the same – let's call it the same temporal phenomenon.

445
00:43:29,320 --> 00:43:33,220
 I would otherwise say event, but I don't want to get the technical sense of event in here.

446
00:43:33,220 --> 00:43:41,580
 And look at something as a now and as an instant from, you know, from these two perspectives.

447
00:43:41,780 --> 00:43:49,840
 You know, Aeon is sort of composed of instances that have no duration, that are only – that are events.

448
00:43:50,360 --> 00:44:01,600
 And Kronos are only nows, which are sort of the mixtures of bodies that have the entire pressures of all futures and pasts sort of imminent to them.

449
00:44:01,600 --> 00:44:04,220
 And sort of expressing through them, right?

450
00:44:05,180 --> 00:44:11,300
 So let's take an example of like Julius Caesar crossing the Rubicon, right?

451
00:44:11,400 --> 00:44:14,800
 And then let's imagine that as a now and as an instance.

452
00:44:15,360 --> 00:44:18,980
 And I have like a starting point, but I don't feel super comfortable with it.

453
00:44:19,020 --> 00:44:21,700
 I'd be curious to see where – how it sparks you.

454
00:44:22,440 --> 00:44:46,180
 So like imagine Caesar crossing the Rubicon as a now and, you know, as a present that contains all futures and pasts that sort of like, you know, you can sort of see all of the pressures or all of the sort of factors and variables that lead to the moment of, you know, of the crossing of the river.

455
00:44:46,180 --> 00:44:55,200
 And then the sort of ways that that then ripples out and sort of sets things into motion into a future, setting out a future.

456
00:44:56,360 --> 00:45:16,820
 So now let's look at that as an instance, which – or think about it as an event that has no duration, that is only dividing – that event is now dividing the past and the future in both directions at once infinitely.

457
00:45:16,820 --> 00:45:28,500
 That is – and it's sort of like a doubling of all futures and pasts that have now been sort of shot through with the inventiveness of Caesar crossing, you know, the Rubicon.

458
00:45:29,040 --> 00:45:33,400
 And in fact, even the language that – the phrase Caesar crosses the Rubicon –

459
00:45:33,400 --> 00:45:34,340
 Right, that's what I was thinking because that's –

460
00:45:34,340 --> 00:45:35,060
 It only makes sense.

461
00:45:35,580 --> 00:45:35,980
 Right.

462
00:45:36,200 --> 00:45:36,440
 Right.

463
00:45:36,860 --> 00:45:42,720
 In that second – like only according to the Aeon does the event Caesar crosses the Rubicon make sense.

464
00:45:42,720 --> 00:45:55,580
 Whereas, you know, from the point of view of the – of Kronos, you know, even calling it that is already – event is already taking on the Aeon's perspective of the thing.

465
00:45:56,780 --> 00:45:56,860
 Right.

466
00:45:56,860 --> 00:46:03,940
 I don't like about that thought experiment as it sort of like imagines like a baseline thing that you would then interpret in two different ways.

467
00:46:04,100 --> 00:46:04,860
 Right, right, right.

468
00:46:04,860 --> 00:46:07,040
 And you have to – you have to sort of like think –

469
00:46:07,040 --> 00:46:09,240
 Well, I mean, no, I mean, that is an interesting question.

470
00:46:09,360 --> 00:46:15,740
 I mean, what it brings – what it brings up for me is kind of the stabilizing function of grammar.

471
00:46:16,520 --> 00:46:20,180
 And that – like, John, you just brought this up.

472
00:46:20,260 --> 00:46:30,620
 Like maybe language's function was not, you know, primarily or ever to represent adequately information or the world.

473
00:46:30,620 --> 00:46:44,300
 But it does seem to me – I mean, again, at least at an experiential level, it seems like grammar and language does – like it has to stabilize something, right?

474
00:46:44,520 --> 00:46:49,320
 Or at least it feels like it has a telos almost embedded in it.

475
00:46:49,620 --> 00:46:52,400
 It's like almost internally fascistic.

476
00:46:52,400 --> 00:47:02,340
 So to me, I feel like, again, like sort of following the elocutionary thinking, I mean, my answer is always going to be some variation on performativity, the elocution specifically.

477
00:47:02,520 --> 00:47:07,640
 But like why – I have no problem with the idea of a slowing down, right?

478
00:47:07,740 --> 00:47:12,980
 Like this is – so language or concepts are ways of slowing down and distributing.

479
00:47:13,240 --> 00:47:15,680
 I mean, you're sort of following the Nietzsche thinking, right?

480
00:47:15,740 --> 00:47:19,940
 Like so it's like we call it a leaf and the moment we call it a leaf, it also becomes a concept.

481
00:47:19,940 --> 00:47:34,100
 But to me, to think of language as a sort of slowing down or a modulating of the speed, let's say it that way, of a modulating of the speed of, say, thinking, I have no problem with that.

482
00:47:34,160 --> 00:47:36,620
 That's not a representation anymore, right?

483
00:47:36,740 --> 00:47:44,440
 Like it is an action and the action is simply one of coagulating, slowing down and stalling stillness so that things aren't just a constant blur.

484
00:47:44,440 --> 00:47:48,280
 Or we call that a leaf instead of a house or whatever.

485
00:47:49,780 --> 00:47:57,020
 And it allows us – I mean, that's where the – at least for me, the kind of pragmatic orientation, which is like, yeah, it lets us do stuff, right?

486
00:47:57,040 --> 00:47:58,560
 It allows us to move around in the world.

487
00:47:58,660 --> 00:47:59,800
 It allows us to have conversations.

488
00:48:00,020 --> 00:48:05,440
 It allows all kinds of relations and interactions that wouldn't otherwise be available.

489
00:48:05,680 --> 00:48:13,800
 But it's just a question of modulating speeds relative to particular organisms and different organisms are going to work differently as we know.

490
00:48:13,960 --> 00:48:16,160
 I mean, conversations are different with different people.

491
00:48:16,160 --> 00:48:21,360
 Well, I was going to say another way of thinking about it is that language doesn't represent eyes.

492
00:48:21,540 --> 00:48:22,840
 It makes eyes, right?

493
00:48:23,040 --> 00:48:35,660
 Like the word eye is always in the process of sort of formulating something around some kind of organizational force of the eye rather than representing an eye that simply exists prior to it.

494
00:48:35,900 --> 00:48:38,560
 And that's one way of thinking about the force of language.

495
00:48:38,560 --> 00:48:44,160
 Yeah, and I just – I mean, all I would add to that is I wouldn't put too much of – like that gives language too much power.

496
00:48:44,700 --> 00:48:47,220
 You know, like language is this determining thing.

497
00:48:47,640 --> 00:48:48,200
 It to me –

498
00:48:48,200 --> 00:48:48,780
 No, it's one –

499
00:48:48,780 --> 00:48:50,000
 It's one –

500
00:48:50,000 --> 00:48:50,440
 Right.

501
00:48:50,760 --> 00:48:56,160
 Like language, conceptuality, like the thing that humans do, I would say, you know, these are an apparatus.

502
00:48:56,160 --> 00:49:03,860
 Like one of the things that we do is we slow down the movement of things so we can produce different kinds of relations with each other and with them, right?

503
00:49:03,940 --> 00:49:13,140
 Like – and so that's – I think in terms of what is, you know, what is philosophy where he talks about like the – and the distinctions are really, I mean, kind of coarse.

504
00:49:13,140 --> 00:49:27,960
 But, you know, the functive, the functive, the job of the functive as opposed to the concept, the job of the functive, the function is to stabilize and concretize something into an identity so that you can do other things with it, right?

505
00:49:28,220 --> 00:49:29,860
 Like so – right, exactly.

506
00:49:30,060 --> 00:49:41,400
 So it's – you know, if you don't – if you don't recognize the existence of a phenomena, you are less able to experiment with it.

507
00:49:42,220 --> 00:49:42,380
 Right.

508
00:49:42,460 --> 00:49:55,500
 And so that's that sense that I've always – like science has never been in the job of producing knowledge or if it has, that's only been a like – it's just kind of a misnomer that in fact science is always in the job of experimentation.

509
00:49:56,380 --> 00:50:13,160
 That's the thing that's always been – that's what's been its driving force and knowledge in quotation marks is just a sort of relay in that process, the sort of slowing down of concrete stuff to a point where we can do a –

510
00:50:13,160 --> 00:50:16,460
 Well, the slowing down of it makes concrete stuff.

511
00:50:16,600 --> 00:50:23,340
 And if you experiment with it one way, I mean, where I would sort of push back on that is that like there's no recognition.

512
00:50:23,580 --> 00:50:40,540
 There's no sort of like phenomenon that exists prior to all of these operations that all of these slowing downs or modulations are simultaneously – like they're not representing or recognizing something that exists prior to it.

513
00:50:40,540 --> 00:50:46,380
 But they're both making the thing and then seeing what that thing can do.

514
00:50:46,620 --> 00:50:49,580
 I mean, that's what I – I mean, I agree with that.

515
00:50:49,700 --> 00:50:51,380
 Like I will totally accept that.

516
00:50:52,300 --> 00:50:54,980
 It's in the job of making things but not on its own.

517
00:50:55,140 --> 00:50:59,620
 Like again, just like I said that about language, I would still say that about our organism, right?

518
00:50:59,700 --> 00:51:01,840
 Like I mean – so it's not the only thing.

519
00:51:02,480 --> 00:51:05,860
 So there are – for instance, we're not making leaves.

520
00:51:05,860 --> 00:51:08,880
 So we're making the concept and the particularly – but there are other forces.

521
00:51:09,500 --> 00:51:10,600
 We call them geological.

522
00:51:10,920 --> 00:51:13,620
 We call them weather and all these sorts of things, right?

523
00:51:13,660 --> 00:51:15,380
 Like there are other forces out there.

524
00:51:16,040 --> 00:51:27,180
 But I mean assembled in the particular nexus, yeah, that we produce understanding, knowledge of these things and see what they can do and what they can't do.

525
00:51:27,180 --> 00:51:34,500
 And this is where Spinoza – like we don't yet know what a body can do as the perpetual state, not like we haven't figured it out yet but we'll get there next week.

526
00:51:34,620 --> 00:51:35,300
 It's like no, no, no.

527
00:51:35,300 --> 00:51:39,960
 The perpetual state is one of we don't know what bodies can do.

528
00:51:51,540 --> 00:52:09,180
 Well, as long as we're talking about language and the power of language – well, there are kind of two things that I want to talk about is one, I mean, is this section on – where you talk – where he sort of like says that language is sort of only made possible because of this – what's the adjectival form of aion?

529
00:52:09,260 --> 00:52:09,780
 Aionic?

530
00:52:10,020 --> 00:52:10,720
 I like that.

531
00:52:11,020 --> 00:52:11,740
 Sure, yeah.

532
00:52:12,360 --> 00:52:14,700
 Aionic dimension of time.

533
00:52:14,700 --> 00:52:28,540
 The other one, thinking about Kronos is, you know, he so nonchalantly flips back and forth between Kronos and Saturn and getting between the Roman and the Greek, you know, articulations of Zeus's father.

534
00:52:29,100 --> 00:52:32,740
 But there's also like Zeus, Kronos slash Saturn.

535
00:52:33,460 --> 00:52:39,140
 And it seems to me that the whole mythological dimension of Zeus eating Kronos – or not – no.

536
00:52:39,580 --> 00:52:42,620
 No, Kronos eats his kids and Zeus kills Kronos.

537
00:52:42,620 --> 00:52:44,160
 Right, Zeus kills Kronos, right.

538
00:52:44,160 --> 00:52:51,460
 Yeah, that dynamic just at least seems a little bit worth, like, keeping in the back of our head.

539
00:52:52,320 --> 00:52:54,080
 I don't care which one you want to get first.

540
00:52:54,400 --> 00:52:55,440
 Let's do the language thing.

541
00:52:55,700 --> 00:52:57,300
 You're on 166, I assume?

542
00:52:57,340 --> 00:52:58,860
 Yeah, yeah, yeah, two there.

543
00:52:59,600 --> 00:53:04,800
 It is this new world of incorporeal effects or surface effects which makes language possible.

544
00:53:05,380 --> 00:53:10,000
 And, like, it was – that first sentence just got me immediately thinking, oh, I'm not going to like this.

545
00:53:10,640 --> 00:53:12,300
 But that quickly changed.

546
00:53:13,120 --> 00:53:26,520
 Because – I mean just because of the way that it was – I anticipated that it was going to make language somehow removed from some kind of real version or, like, make language not bodily enough or material enough.

547
00:53:26,980 --> 00:53:27,600
 Oh, okay.

548
00:53:28,080 --> 00:53:35,980
 When I read that, I read, like, the illocutionary is the condition of possibility for locution.

549
00:53:36,160 --> 00:53:37,760
 Like, that's actually what I read.

550
00:53:37,820 --> 00:53:39,520
 When I read that sentence, that's how I read it.

551
00:53:39,620 --> 00:53:40,680
 I'm like, yeah, that seems right.

552
00:53:42,760 --> 00:53:44,320
 Too much bullshit in my life.

553
00:53:46,840 --> 00:53:47,240
 Okay.

554
00:53:48,120 --> 00:53:58,020
 So, for, as we shall see, it is this world which draws the sound from their simple state of corporeal action and passions.

555
00:53:58,920 --> 00:54:08,640
 It is this new world which distinguishes language, prevents it being from confused with sound effects of bodies, and abstracts it from their oral-anal determinations.

556
00:54:09,280 --> 00:54:14,120
 It's not just grunts and farts anymore, but it becomes language.

557
00:54:14,120 --> 00:54:29,020
 Pure events ground language because they wait for it as much as they wait for us and have a pure, singular, impersonal, and pre-individual existence only inside the language which expresses them.

558
00:54:29,600 --> 00:54:34,580
 It is what is expressed in its independence that grounds language and expression.

559
00:54:34,580 --> 00:54:48,560
 It is the metaphysical property that sounds acquire in order to have a sense, and, secondarily, to signify, manifest, and denote, rather than to belong to bodies as physical qualities.

560
00:54:49,180 --> 00:54:59,580
 So, that's not terribly, I mean, just as an addendum, like, that's not terribly dissimilar from the way that you were describing this kind of passive precondition of the faculties in context.

561
00:54:59,600 --> 00:55:10,300
 That you have here, this is sort of the evental precondition for, you know, for signification, manifestation, and denotation, right?

562
00:55:10,420 --> 00:55:15,620
 Like, which are the three functions of language that he talked about, like, in series two or whatever.

563
00:55:16,140 --> 00:55:21,880
 Except for the fact that this pre-individuality and personality is not a generality.

564
00:55:22,760 --> 00:55:24,060
 That's right, that's right.

565
00:55:24,060 --> 00:55:33,500
 Like, I mean, these are evolving events that sort of then, you could say, infect or are incorporated, right?

566
00:55:33,840 --> 00:55:36,640
 Or sort of, I mean, never quite, they never become bodies.

567
00:55:36,980 --> 00:55:46,460
 Whereas, for Kant, that perhaps pre-individual operation is happening at the general level of the human mind.

568
00:55:46,960 --> 00:55:52,180
 And then it gets sort of disseminated down to individual human minds who use them better or worse.

569
00:55:52,740 --> 00:56:01,860
 So, think about this as a possible follow-up from what you just said, is that we always think of language acquisition as something that people sort of go through at a certain age, right?

570
00:56:01,900 --> 00:56:05,420
 Like, whatever two years old, you know, one to two years old, whatever age it is.

571
00:56:05,740 --> 00:56:10,860
 And that, you know, relative degrees of completeness and sophistication, and then, you know, we're in language now.

572
00:56:11,100 --> 00:56:21,820
 But I feel like what's being said there is the entry into language is so dispersed, we don't all go through this process of, and that's another place where the word language is just inadequate.

573
00:56:22,160 --> 00:56:32,500
 Because what we do, what each of us does with words isn't the same thing, that we are not particulars of a general process of acquiring language.

574
00:56:33,320 --> 00:56:52,920
 I mean, if events, right, are this kind of precondition, then it is so fully singular, I mean, that's a ridiculous phrase, but it's so singular as to, you know, sort of erase or eradicate the idea that the three of us have language.

575
00:56:52,920 --> 00:56:58,620
 Not even that we have English or a language, but that we all have some version of the same thing.

576
00:56:58,940 --> 00:57:02,000
 And it's like, no, I mean, I think one of the, that would be one of the upshots, right?

577
00:57:02,040 --> 00:57:10,760
 Is that there, there isn't just like this general capacity to acquire, this is where the, the sort of linguistics folks would be like, that doesn't make any sense.

578
00:57:10,960 --> 00:57:11,160
 Yeah.

579
00:57:11,380 --> 00:57:11,920
 I would think.

580
00:57:12,040 --> 00:57:18,900
